Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing state law requires the Department of Health and Human Services, through the
2 Division of Welfare and Supportive Services of the Department, to administer certain
3 programs of public assistance. (NRS 232.320, 422A.338) Under existing federal law, any
4 officer or employee of any State who is authorized by federal law to obtain information from
5 federal tax returns for the purpose of administering provisions of state or federal law is
6 prohibited from disclosing any information obtained from those returns. (26 U.S.C. § 6103)
7 As a condition of receiving such information, federal law requires state officers and
8 employees to comply with certain safeguards prescribed by the United States Secretary of the
9 Treasury to ensure the confidentiality of the federal tax returns and the information contained
10 in those returns. (26 U.S.C. § 6103(p)(4)) Publication 1075 of the United States Internal
11 Revenue Service: (1) establishes the “Tax Information Security Guidelines for Federal, State
12 and Local Agencies” to provide guidance to federal, state and local agencies to ensure that the
13 policies, practices, controls and safeguards of those agencies adequately protect the
14 confidentiality of federal taxpayer information; and (2) includes in those Guidelines
15 requirements related to conducting background investigations of employees and contractors of
16 an agency that have access to federal taxpayer information.
17 Assembly Bill No. 530 of the 2019 Session of the Nevada Legislature requires: (1) the
18 Department of Taxation to conduct a background investigation of each employee or contractor
19 of the Department upon initial employment or contract and at least once every 5 years
20 thereafter; and (2) such employees and contractors to submit to the Department proof of

